    faqs: [{question:"Is a Bitcoin ETF better than buying Bitcoin directly?",answer:"It depends on your priorities. ETFs are simpler (no wallet management, no keys to secure) and fit into existing brokerage and retirement accounts. Direct Bitcoin ownership provides full control, 24/7 trading, and no management fees. ETFs charge annual fees that compound over time. For retirement accounts and traditional investors, ETFs are more practical. For crypto-native users, direct ownership is often preferred."},{question:"Do Bitcoin ETFs hold actual Bitcoin?",answer:"Spot Bitcoin ETFs hold physical Bitcoin in custody. When you buy shares of a spot ETF like BlackRock's IBIT, the fund buys equivalent Bitcoin stored in institutional-grade cold storage. Futures ETFs do not hold Bitcoin directly — they hold Bitcoin futures contracts that track the price. Spot ETFs provide closer price tracking with less structural drag."},{question:"Can I buy Bitcoin ETFs in my 401k?",answer:"It depends on your employer's 401k plan. Some plans have added Bitcoin ETF options, but most have not yet. You may be able to access Bitcoin ETFs through self-directed brokerage windows within your 401k if available. IRA accounts offer more flexibility — most major brokerages now allow Bitcoin ETF purchases in Traditional and Roth IRAs."}],
